The American National Election Studies surveys a representative sample of US voters prior to and following each US Presidential Election. We will use their survey from the last US Presidential Election (held in 2024) to learn more about US voters.

Tip

The nes2024 data set in the polsciols R package provides you with a selection of the hundreds of questions the ANES asked of all 5,521 respondents to the 2024 survey. Each row provides data for one respondent.

For this problem set, only include observations for which full responses were recorded (exclude those who, for any question included in the dataset, refused to answer it, didnât know the answer, or have missing responses).

Part B

Points: 2

Describe the distribution of the total number of respondents that obtained each highest level of education. Include a plot of those counts.

HighestEducation <- 
  nes2024 %>% 
  select(education) %>% 
  mutate(count = 1)

HighestEducation %>% 
  group_by(education) %>% 
  summarise(totalcount = sum(count, na.rm = T)) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = totalcount, y = education, na.rm = T)) +
  geom_col()+
  theme_minimal()

Question 5

The ANES also asked respondents prior to the election to rate Kamala Harris and Donald Trump on a scale from 0 to 100.

Part A

Points: 3

Plot all respondentsâ answers to these two questions on a single density plot. There are several peaks in these distributions. What do these peaks have in common? What might they suggest about how people answer questions that ask them to provide a single number along a large range?

NesCandidate<- pivot_longer(
  data = nes2024, 
  cols = c('therm_harris', 'therm_trump'),
  names_to = "candidate",
  values_to = "Rate") %>% 
  group_by(candidate) %>% 
  ggplot() +
  geom_density(alpha = 0.7, aes(x = Rate, fill = candidate)) + labs(
    title = "Rate Harris and Trump on a scale from 0 to 100") +
  theme_minimal()+
  scale_fill_manual(values=c("#274753", "#8D2F25"))
  
NesCandidate

Both of the peaks are at 0, it might suggest about people trend to answer the smallest value for show their dislike when they answer questions that ask them to provide a single number along a large range.

Part B

Points: 3

President Trump won this election. Would you predict this outcome from the way this representative sample responded to these questions? Provide a brief description of the reasoning behind your answer.

It is difficult to predict the outcome from this sample because:

  1. We lack evidence that strong disapproval of Trump translates directly into support for Harris (and vice versa); the relationship between the two measures is unclear.

  2. The demographic composition of the respondents is not specified, which limits our ability to generalize.

  3. There may be selection bias, as individuals who participate in such polls are often those with at least some post-high school education and a strong interest in politics.
